<subSubSection id="2E9B6511DD1A5A33FF7AFD6ACECDCA3E" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" type="description">
<paragraph id="663E369ADD1A5A33FF7AFD6ACD92CC95" blockId="24.[227,436,709,735]" box="[227,436,709,735]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<heading id="3D7681F6DD1A5A33FF7AFD6ACD92CC95" bold="true" box="[227,436,709,735]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" reason="3">
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1A5A33FF7AFD6ACD92CC95" bold="true" box="[227,436,709,735]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Shell description</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="663E369ADD1A5A33FF7AFD5BC8D0CDF4" blockId="24.[226,1437,756,958]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
Large-sized shell (SL max.: l 
<quantity id="A1799B7FDD1A5A33FDA5FD5BCE9FCD44" box="[572,697,756,782]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.384" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" unit="mm" value="83.84">83.84 mm</quantity>
), with hemispherical-shaped spire and smooth shoulder. Early spire whorls convex, smooth, resulting in flat to convex outline. Later spire whorls strongly convex, elevated. Suture channelled, irregular. Subsutural flexure very deep, moderately curved, strongly asymmetrical (
<figureCitation id="FEBA2A1FDD1A5A33FE0FFCF2CE2FCD3D" box="[406,521,861,887]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="61.[227,270,1647,1673]" captionTargetBox="[227,1437,912,1604]" captionTargetId="figure-374@61.[227,1437,912,1604]" captionTargetPageId="61" captionText="Fig. 40. Examples of subsutural flexures. A. Conus (Lautoconus) eschewegi Pereira da Costa, 1866 (MNHN.F.A82976). B. Conus (Lautoconus) ictini sp. nov. (AMPG(IV) 3719). C. Conus (Lautoconus) sp. 1 (MNHN.F.A82982). D. Conus (Lautoconus) sp. 2 (AMPG(IV) 3756). E. Conus (Lautoconus) sp. 3 (MNHN.F.A83012). F. Conus (Lautoconus) cf. baldichieri Borson, 1820 (MNHN.F.A83013). G. Conus (Lautoconus) lauriatragei sp. nov. (MNHN.F.A83014). H. Conus (Lautoconus) damianakisi sp. nov. (AMPG(IV) 3802). I. Conus (Lautoconus) sp. 4 (MNHN.F.A83015). J. Conus (Lautoconus) sp. 5 (AMPG(IV) 3861). K. Conus (Stephanoconus) cf. taurinensis Bellardi &amp; Michelotti, 1841 (AMPG(IV) 3808). L. Conus (Stephanoconus) moissettei sp. nov. (MNHN.F.A83071). M. Conus davolii sp. nov. (MNHN.F.A83091). N. Conus fuscocingulatus Hörnes, 1851 (AMPG(IV) 3858). O. Conus (Plagioconus) elatus Michelotti, 1847 (AMPG(IV) 3862). P. Conus (Plagioconus) sp. (AMPG(IV) 3890). Q. Conus (Plagioconus) sp. (AMPG(IV) 3898). R. Conus (Plagioconus) aquensis d’Orbigny, 1852 (AMPG(IV) 3907). Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6484351" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6484351/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Fig. 40G</figureCitation>
). Shoulder smooth, with maximum diameter at shoulder. Aperture narrow, curved. Last whorl conical, straight to concave, narrowing slightly at centre of last whorl. Deeply carved growth lines on last whorl. Aperture not straight, wavy. Fasciole very small, to indistinct.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="663E369ADD1A5A33FF7AFC4ACE69CDB5" blockId="24.[227,591,997,1023]" box="[227,591,997,1023]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<heading id="3D7681F6DD1A5A33FF7AFC4ACE69CDB5" bold="true" box="[227,591,997,1023]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" reason="3">
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1A5A33FF7AFC4ACE69CDB5" bold="true" box="[227,591,997,1023]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Description of colour pattern</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="663E369ADD1A5A33FF7AFBBCCECDCA3E" blockId="24.[227,1436,1043,1140]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
Shell surface partly damaged (
<figureCitation id="FEBA2A1FDD1A5A33FDD3FBBCCE87CA64" box="[586,673,1043,1070]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="23.[227,270,1966,1992]" captionTargetBox="[227,1437,1100,1936]" captionTargetId="figure-148@23.[227,1437,1100,1936]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="Fig. 13. Conus (Lautoconus) lauriatragei sp. nov,, specimen MNHN.F.A83014 from the late Miocene of Tylissos, Crete (Greece) in apertural, abapertural and apical views, under natural (A2, A4) and UV light. Scale bar = 1 cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6484293" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6484293/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
). The visible colour pattern consists of wide, axial flammulae on the spire whorls, that continue axially as ribbons on the body of the shell. The ribbons are connected with irregular fluorescent blotches (
<figureCitation id="FEBA2A1FDD1A5A33FD1FFBF5CEF8CA3E" box="[646,734,1114,1140]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="24.[229,272,2000,2026]" captionTargetBox="[227,1437,1536,1969]" captionTargetId="figure-311@24.[227,1437,1536,1969]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="Fig. 14. Colour pattern of irregular blotches and axial ribbons on Conus (Lautoconus) lauriatragei sp. nov. MNHN.F.A83014 from the late Miocene of Tylissos, Crete (Greece). Scale bar = 1 cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6484295" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6484295/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2E9B6511DD1A5A32FF7AFB33CDA1CC4D" lastPageId="25" lastPageNumber="26" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="663E369ADD1A5A33FF7AFB33CD73CAFC" blockId="24.[227,341,1180,1206]" box="[227,341,1180,1206]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<heading id="3D7681F6DD1A5A33FF7AFB33CD73CAFC" bold="true" box="[227,341,1180,1206]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" reason="3">
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1A5A33FF7AFB33CD73CAFC" bold="true" box="[227,341,1180,1206]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="663E369ADD1A5A32FF7AFB65CF77CF24" blockId="24.[226,1437,1226,1464]" lastBlockId="25.[227,1436,303,366]" lastPageId="25" lastPageNumber="26" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
This species is quite unusual in morphology (
<tableCitation id="2B030321DD1A5A33FC8FFB65CF50CAAE" box="[790,886,1226,1252]" captionStart="Table 7" captionStartId="24.[227,296,303,329]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="Table 7. Shell measurements and ratios of Conus (Lautoconus) lauriatragei sp. nov. MNHN.F.A83014 from the late Miocene of Tylissos, Crete (Greece)." pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Table 7</tableCitation>
), being very large with a semi-circular spire outline species of 
<taxonomicName id="A1814D19DD1A5A33FE48FB41CEEFCB42" authority="" authorityName="Monterosato" authorityYear="1923" box="[465,713,1261,1288]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Mollusca" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Lautoconus">
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1A5A33FE48FB41CE3ACB42" box="[465,540,1262,1288]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Conus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1A5A33FDAFFB41CE99CB4D" box="[566,703,1262,1287]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Lautoconus</emphasis>
)
</taxonomicName>
with a similar morphology occur today, such as 
<taxonomicName id="A1814D19DD1A5A33FAC8FB41CE88CB61" authority="Rolan &amp; Trovao" authorityName="Rolan &amp; Trovao" authorityYear="1990" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="regonae" subGenus="Lautoconus">
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1A5A33FAC8FB41C9BACB42" box="[1361,1436,1262,1288]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Conus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1A5A33FF74FABECD50CB60" box="[237,374,1297,1322]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Lautoconus</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1A5A33FE1EFABECDC0CB60" box="[391,486,1297,1322]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">regonae</emphasis>
Rolán &amp; Trovão
</taxonomicName>
in Rolán, 1990 (see 
<bibRefCitation id="02104B6BDD1A5A33FC3AFABFC8AECB60" author="Tenorio M. J. &amp; Abalde S. &amp; Pardos-Blas J. R. &amp; Zardoya R." box="[931,1160,1296,1323]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" pagination="1 - 89" refId="ref32106" refString="Tenorio M. J., Abalde S., Pardos-Blas J. R. &amp; Zardoya R. 2020. Taxonomic revision of West African cone snails (Gastropoda: Conidae) based upon mitogenomic studies: implications for conservation. European Journal of Taxonomy (663): 1 - 89. https: // doi. org / 10.5852 / ejt. 2020.663" type="journal article" year="2020">
Tenorio 
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1A5A33FB9FFABEC81FCB60" box="[1030,1081,1296,1322]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">et al</emphasis>
. 2020
</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 6d). Therefore, we are confident in assigning it to this subgenus. Other than the Cretan specimen, another specimen called 
<taxonomicName id="A1814D19DD1A5A33FF7AFAF8CDF3CB3B" authority="" authorityName="Monterosato" authorityYear="1923" box="[227,469,1367,1393]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Mollusca" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Lautoconus">
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1A5A33FF7AFAF8CD08CB3B" box="[227,302,1367,1393]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Conus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1A5A33FEDBFAF7CDEDCB3B" box="[322,459,1368,1393]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Lautoconus</emphasis>
)
</taxonomicName>
sp. (HNHM INV 2013.291; 
<bibRefCitation id="02104B6BDD1A5A33FCACFAF8C86CCB3B" author="Kovacs Z. &amp; Vician Z." box="[821,1098,1367,1393]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" pagination="53 - 100" refId="ref30426" refString="Kovacs Z. &amp; Vician Z. 2013. Badenian (Middle Miocene) Conoidean (Neogastropoda) fauna from Letkes (N Hungary). Fragmenta Palaeontologica Hungarica 30: 53 - 100." type="journal article" year="2013">Kovács &amp; Vicián 2013</bibRefCitation>
) has also been found in the Paratethys from the Pannonian Basin at Letkés, 
<collectingCountry id="1E96760ADD1A5A33FC8BFAD5CF5CCBDE" box="[786,890,1402,1428]" name="Hungary" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Hungary</collectingCountry>
, and for us it could belong to the same species. Its colour pattern is not comparable to any of the 
<taxonomicName id="A1814D19DD1A5A33FCA0FA32CFBDCBFD" authorityName="Fleming" authorityYear="1822" box="[825,923,1437,1463]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Mollusca" rank="family">Conidae</taxonomicName>
studied herein. Despite not having at least three shells of this species found so far (
<bibRefCitation id="02104B6BDD1B5A32FD20FE80CF5CCF00" author="Hendricks J. R." box="[697,890,303,330]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="0120924" refId="ref29781" refString="Hendricks J. R. 2015. Glowing seashells: diversity of fossilized coloration patterns on coral reefassociated cone snail (Gastropoda: Conidae) shells from the Neogene of the Dominican Republic. PLoS One 10 (4): e 0120924. https: // doi. org / 10.1371 / journal. pone. 0120924" type="journal article" year="2015">Hendricks 2015</bibRefCitation>
), due to the unique morphology of this species we name it 
<taxonomicName id="A1814D19DD1B5A32FEF2FEFBCEC9CF24" authority="Psarras &amp; Merle &amp; Koskeridou, 2022" authorityName="Psarras &amp; Merle &amp; Koskeridou" authorityYear="2022" box="[363,751,340,366]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="lauriatragei" status="sp. nov." subGenus="Lautoconus">
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1B5A32FEF2FEFBCD90CF24" box="[363,438,340,366]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Conus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1B5A32FE5EFEFACE76CF24" box="[455,592,341,366]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Lautoconus</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1B5A32FDF8FEFBCEC9CF24" box="[609,751,340,366]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">lauriatragei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="4FC657F3DD1B5A32FD6FFEFBCF77CF24" box="[758,849,340,366]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
